"Perhaps. Or perhaps you're both reading different rounds, different moments. What matters now is this: you've both stopped giving entirely. The garden is empty. No stars grow here anymore."

The Star Weaver looked around. It was true. Where there had once been exchanges—even failed ones—now there was only silence. Two beings, each convinced the other had betrayed them first, each watching the other with dark suspicion.

"Who broke trust first matters less than who restores it," the Tortoise said.

"But restoration requires risk," the Star Weaver replied. "And risk requires trust."

"Yes," said the Tortoise. "That is the paradox. And that is why most gardens stay barren."

The Star Weaver stood between the pedestals, considering.
